          "$type": "text",
          "text": "# James's Return-to-Running Plan\n\n## First, a word before the plan\n\nJames, welcome — and genuinely, well done for getting here. Coming back from plantar fasciitis takes patience that most runners find harder than the training itself. The fact that you've been building carefully, staying at easy pace, and noting how your foot feels along the way? That's exactly the kind of process that leads to durable comebacks. Your recent sessions show real consistency, and that's what this plan is built on.\n\nBefore I walk you through everything, I want to check in: **how is the foot feeling right now, as of your most recent run?** And is there anything your physio flagged specifically — any movements, surfaces, or warning signs they want you to watch for? That context will help me make sure this plan fits what they've cleared you for.\n\n---\n\n## Understanding Your Starting Point\n\nHere's what the data tells me, and the reasoning behind every decision in this plan:\n\nYour pre-injury VDOT of 46.5 (from your 44:00 10K) gives us a reliable fitness ceiling — but your *current* fitness is almost certainly lower after the layoff. More importantly, your physio has cleared you for **easy running only, up to 20 minutes, with walking breaks if there's any foot pain**. That clearance is the governing constraint here, not your fitness level. The plan respects that fully.\n\nYour recent training shows a sensible pattern: you've been running 3x/week at 5:58/km (the conservative end of your easy range), building from 15 to 20 minutes. That's the foundation we're extending.\n\n---\n\n## Pace Guidance\n\nYour prescribed paces come from your 44:00 10K via Daniels' Running Formula:\n\n| Type | Pace Range |\n|---|---|\n| **Easy (your current zone)** | 5:24 – 5:58 /km |\n| Marathon | 4:44 /km |\n| Threshold | 4:29 /km |\n| Interval | 4:12 /km |\n| Repetition | 3:57 /km |\n\n**For this entire plan, you're running at 5:45–5:58/km — the comfortable end of easy.** The faster end of easy (5:24) and everything above it stays off the table until your physio clears you for more. This isn't a limitation — it's how you protect the tissue adaptation that's happening right now. Connective tissue like the plantar fascia remodels more slowly than cardiovascular fitness, and easy pace is the stimulus it needs.\n\n---\n\n## The Plan: 8 Weeks, 3 Phases\n\n### Structure Logic\n- **3 days/week** — Tuesday, Thursday, Saturday (long run day)\n- **Volume increases no more than 10% per week**\n- **Deload every 4th week** (volume drops ~20%)\n- **No speed work** until physio clearance\n- **Walking breaks** built into early weeks; you decide whether to use them based on how your foot feels that day\n- Saturday is your longest run of the week\n\n---\n\n### PHASE 1 — Consolidate (Weeks 1–3)\n*Goal: Establish consistent 20-minute runs without foot symptoms. Build the habit before building the load.*\n\n**Week 1** | Total: ~10 km\n| Day | Session | Duration | Notes |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Tuesday | Easy run | 20 min | 5:50–5:58/km. Walk break at 10 min if any foot tightness |\n| Thursday | Easy run | 18 min | 5:50–5:58/km |\n| Saturday | Easy run | 20 min | 5:50–5:58/km. Your \"long run\" for now |\n\n**Week 2** | Total: ~10.5 km\n| Day | Session | Duration | Notes |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Tuesday | Easy run | 20 min | 5:45–5:58/km |\n| Thursday | Easy run | 20 min | 5:45–5:58/km |\n| Saturday | Easy run | 20 min | 5:45–5:58/km |\n\n**Week 3** | Total: ~11 km\n| Day | Session | Duration | Notes |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Tuesday | Easy run | 20 min | 5:45–5:58/km |\n| Thursday | Easy run | 20 min | 5:45–5:58/km |\n| Saturday | Easy run | 22 min | First small extension — only if Week 2 was symptom-free |\n\n> **Phase 1 checkpoint:** If you complete Week 3 with no foot pain during or after runs, and no morning heel stiffness lasting more than a few minutes, you're ready for Phase 2. If symptoms flare, stay in Phase 1 and check back in with your physio.\n\n---\n\n### PHASE 2 — Build Duration (Weeks 4–6)\n*Goal: Extend the Saturday long run while keeping Tuesday/Thursday steady. Introduce the concept of \"time on feet.\"*\n\n**Week 4 — Deload** | Total: ~9 km\n| Day | Session | Duration | Notes |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Tuesday | Easy run | 18 min | Pull back intentionally. This is investment, not regression |\n| Thursday | Easy run | 18 min | 5:45–5:58/km |\n| Saturday | Easy run | 20 min | 5:50–5:58/km |\n\n**Week 5** | Total: ~12 km\n| Day | Session | Duration | Notes |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Tuesday | Easy run | 20 min | 5:45–5:58/km |\n| Thursday | Easy run | 20 min | 5:45–5:58/km |\n| Saturday | Easy run | 25 min | 5:50–5:58/km. Walk break available at 15 min if needed |\n\n**Week 6** | Total: ~13 km\n| Day | Session | Duration | Notes |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Tuesday | Easy run | 20 min | 5:45–5:58/km |\n| Thursday | Easy run | 22 min | 5:45–5:58/km |\n| Saturday | Easy run | 28 min | 5:50–5:58/km |\n\n> **Phase 2 checkpoint:** How is morning foot stiffness trending? If it's consistently resolving within 5 minutes and you're not modifying your gait during runs, that's a strong signal. This is also a good moment to schedule a follow-up with your physio if you haven't already — getting their eyes on your progress before Phase 3 is worth it.\n\n---\n\n### PHASE 3 — Extend & Prepare for Next Stage (Weeks 7–8)\n*Goal: Reach 30+ minutes on the long run, consolidate 3x/week running, and set up a conversation with your physio about what comes next.*\n\n**Week 7** | Total: ~14.5 km\n| Day | Session | Duration | Notes |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Tuesday | Easy run | 22 min | 5:40–5:55/km — you can start exploring the middle of your easy range |\n| Thursday | Easy run | 22 min | 5:40–5:55/km |\n| Saturday | Easy run | 30 min | 5:50–5:58/km. A real milestone — take it easy and enjoy it |\n\n**Week 8 — Deload + Assessment** | Total: ~12 km\n| Day | Session | Duration | Notes |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Tuesday | Easy run | 20 min | 5:45–5:58/km |\n| Thursday | Easy run | 20 min | 5:45–5:58/km |\n| Saturday | Easy run | 25 min | 5:50–5:58/km. Reflect on the 8 weeks |\n\n---\n\n## What Happens After Week 8?\n\nIf you reach Week 8 symptom-free, you'll be running ~3x/week, up to 30 minutes, with a solid base under you. At that point, the natural next conversation with your physio is: **am I cleared to increase duration further, and when can we introduce some light intensity?**\n\nOnce you have that clearance, there's a clear path back toward your pre-injury fitness — and eventually, back toward that 44:00 10K and beyond. That's not a distant dream; it's a logical next chapter.\n\n---\n\n## Daily Foot Check-In Protocol\n\nBefore every run, do a quick self-assessment:\n\n- **Morning heel pain:** A little stiffness that resolves in under 5 minutes = okay to run. Pain that lingers or causes you to limp = rest day, contact physio if it persists.\n- **During the run:** Any sharp pain, altered gait, or compensating = stop, walk home, log it.\n- **After the run:** Some mild fatigue is normal. Pain that worsens in the hours after = flag it.\n\n**The rule of thumb your physio likely gave you still applies here: 0–2/10 discomfort is generally acceptable during return-to-run. Anything above that is a signal to back off.**\n\n---\n\n## A Note on the Paces\n\nYou might notice that 5:58/km feels almost too easy — like you're barely working. That's correct, and it's the point. Your cardiovascular system could handle more right now. Your plantar fascia cannot. Easy running at this stage is doing real physiological work: it's stimulating collagen remodeling in the fascia, building aerobic base, and reinforcing the neuromuscular patterns of running — all without overloading healing tissue. The restraint *is* the training.\n\n---\n\nSo, James — how does this feel as a starting point? And I'm still curious about that foot check-in: how has it been feeling after your most recent runs?"
        }
